properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the King River
 at the Docker Road Bridge.

King River at Docker Road Bridge

MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY OVERNIGHT THURSDAY AT DOCKER ROAD BRIDGE

Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge and major flooding is likely from overnight Thursday. 

The King River downstream of Lake William Hovell is currently at 1.63 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. 
The King River downstream of Lake William Hovell is likely to exceed the minor flood level (1.80 m) Thursday afternoon. 

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 4.00 metres and rising, with moderate flooding. 
The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is likely to reach the major flood level (4.10 m) overnight Thursday into Friday with forecast rainfall.

Since 9:00 am Thursday, rainfall totals of 10-35 mm have been observed in the Ovens and King River catchment. Additional widespread heavy rainfall is forecast for Thursday and into Friday and further river level rises are possible. A severe weather warning for heavy rainfall is current across the catchment
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • At the Moderate Flood Level (3.95m), low-lying farmland is likely to be affected. 
  • Docker-Carboor Road is likely to be closed between Wangaratta-Whitfield Road & Oxley-Meadow Creek Road due to flooding.
  • Other local roads may be closed due to flooding.
  • At the Major Flood Level (4.1m), flooding will increase in farmland along the river.
  • At Gentle Annie Caravan Park, the King River approaches the top of the bank.
  • Whitfield-Wangaratta Road at Edi may start to flood.
  • Johnstons Bridge on Lake Buffalo to Whitfield Rd at Black Range Creek may be close to inundation.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Flash Flood Watch and Act is being issued for Hawthorn. 

  • Heavy rainfall is causing localised flash flooding. 
  • You can stay safe by avoiding flooded and low-lying areas. 
  • Floodwater can be very deep, rise quickly and move fast. 
  • Be aware that heavy rainfall may also increase the potential for landslides and debris across roads.
If you are located in Hawthorn, you are in danger. You should immediately move indoors, away from floodwater. Do not enter floodwater.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are inside: 
  • Stay inside and be aware of rising floodwater. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

If you are outside: 
  • You should stay away from trees, drains, low lying areas, creeks, canals, culverts and floodwater. 
  • You should seek shelter indoors, away from floodwater. 

If you are driving: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Homes and buildings could be flooded. 
  • Power, Water, Sewerage and telephone services could be lost in the area. 
  • Roads or bridges could be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.   

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 11:50 pm or as the situation changes.

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MINOR FLOODING AT SHEPPARTON LIKELY FROM FRIDAY AFTERNOON.

Rapid and significant river level rises are occurring along the Goulburn River and its tributaries. Major flooding is occurring along the Yea River, Hughes Creek and Sunday Creek, with river levels still rising. Major flooding is expected at Seymour from Thursday evening. Further rises are expected with forecast rainfall during Thursday.

Minor flooding is expected to extend downstream to Shepparton from Friday afternoon, with further rises likely. Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated once upstream locations have peaked.

In the 24 hours to 11:00 am Thursday, widespread rainfall totals of 30-80 mm have been observed in the Goulburn River catchment. Further rainfall totals of 30-50 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday into Friday, with isolated higher totals possible.

Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton:

Minor flooding is likely along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 7.46 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Murchison is likely to exceed the minor flood level (9.00 m) Thursday night. Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall.

The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 9.12 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is likely to exceed the minor flood level (9.50 m) Friday afternoon. Further rises are possible as upstream floodwaters arrive.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

This Flood Watch is being issued for the Upper Murray Catchment.

MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY ACROSS A NUMBER OF NORTHERN VICTORIAN CATCHMENTS AND WIDESPREAD MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED ACROSS NORTHERN AND PARTS OF WESTERN VICTORIA

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

A cold front is moving into the west of the state, bringing showers and rain. Rainfall will increase during Thursday and Friday, HEAVY RAINFALL which may lead to FLASH FLOODING is forecast for northern and western Victoria from overnight Wednesday, extending into central and northeastern parts during Thursday morning. Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet as a result of the recent rainfall and river levels are elevated within some catchments.

From Wednesday to Friday, rainfall totals of 60-100 mm are forecast north of the divide, while rainfall totals of 30-60 mm are forecast south of the divide. 

Flooding is likely to develop from Thursday. Widespread Minor to Major flooding is expected across Northern Victoria and parts of Western Victoria. Isolated Minor flooding is possible in parts of Gippsland.

Catchments likely to be affected include:
Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers 
Kiewa River 
Ovens & King Rivers
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Find local flood information and practical advice about how to prepare at www.ses.vic.gov.au 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 01:50 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.name: Warning
properties.webBody:
This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek
 and replaces the warning issued yesterday for the same event. 

  • A landslide has occurred on the Bogong - High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
  • There is a slow moving active landslide on Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Regional Roads Victoria has undertaken geotechnical investigations at the site and implemented traffic management measures limiting Bogong - High Plains Road to one lane in this area, with reduced speed also in place.
  • With heavy rainfall forecast for the region this week and into next week, a full closure of Bogong - High Plains Road is in effect from midday on Wednesday 12 October. 
  • From now, access to and from Falls Creek will only be allowed for emergency services and essential services. 
  • When the road will re-open has not been determined and will depend on weather conditions and ongoing management of the landslide risk.
  • Regional Roads Victoria will continue to monitor the landslide risk and potential impact on Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Geotechnical experts will complete assessments of the site and determine the best course of action to address the risk
Stay safe by avoiding fallen trees and powerlines, blocked or damaged roads and the area in general. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide.

The Bogong High - Plains Road at Bogong IS NOW CLOSED from Mt Beauty as planned from midday on Wednesday 12 October in anticipation of poor weather worsening the landslide.

Road users can no longer enter or exit Falls Creek or the Bogong Village from either direction on the Bogong High - Plans Road. 

What you should do:
  • If you have chosen to remain, expect to be unable to leave for three days until the extreme weather has passed and the road is safely cleared. 
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landside occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, powerlines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Driving:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
  • There is now no access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong - High Plains Road is closed. 
  • The Bogong High Plains Road on the other side of Falls Creek remains closed due to snow and will likely remain that way for several more weeks.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#viclandslide).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM CAIRN CURRANMAJOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM LAANECOORIE RESERVOIR OVERNIGHT THURSDAY INTO FRIDAY
  • MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LODDON WEIR AND APPIN SOUTH
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in parts of the Loddon River, with renewed rises from overnight rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream through the catchment. 
  • Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall.
  • Major flooding is occurring at Downstream Cairn Curran and expected at Downstream Laanecoorie Reservoir from overnight Thursday into Friday. 
  • Moderate flooding has is occurring along the Loddon River at Appin South. 
  • The Loddon River Downstream Loddon Weir is steady around the moderate flood level.
  • In the 24 hours to 3:00 pm Thursday, rainfall totals of 40-65 mm have been observed across the Loddon River catchment. 
  • Further heavy rainfall is forecast for Thursday and into Friday.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 01:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Ovens River to Bright.
  •  This Watch and Act message replaces the minor flood warning issued at 10.20am. 
  • Rainfall will increase during Thursday and Friday as a cold front moves slowly eastwards. 
  • Minor flooding is expected to develop along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge from Thursday morning. 
  • Further rises are expected with forecast rainfall and major flooding is likely from overnight Thursday. 
  •  Minor flooding is occurring along the Fifteen Mile Creek and moderate flooding is possible from overnight Thursday.
  •  Minor flooding is likely to develop along the Ovens River and along the Buffalo River from overnight Thursday. 
  • Further rises to the moderate flood level are likely with forecast rainfall. In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Thursday, rainfall totals of 20-100 mm have been observed in the Ovens and King River catchment.
  •  Further rainfall totals of 50-120 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and into Friday. 
  •  A severe weather warning for heavy rainfall is current across the catchment.
  • Moderate flooding may occur along the Ovens River to Bright.
  •  The Ovens River at Bright is currently at 1.81 metres and rising, below the minor flood level. 
  • The Ovens River at Bright is likely to exceed the minor flood level (3.00 m) overnight Thursday into Friday. 
  • The river level may reach the moderate flood level (3.60 m) during Friday, with forecast rainfall
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground if still safe to do so.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you will be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
Between Harrietville and Bright
  • Flash flooding may result  from local rainfall on the bushfire -affected catchment of East Branch with breakout flows downstream (north) of Feathertop Lane. 
  • The first part of the Great Alpine Road to flood in this area is often at Frosty Corner (north of Harrietville near the trout farm) which isolates Harrietville.
  • At Stony Creek, flooding over the Stony Creek Bridge isolates properties in Stony Creek Rd, Pinchgut Lane and Millers Track.
  • At Freeburgh, flooding over the Freeburgh Bridge isolates residents in Old Harrietville Rd, Snowy Creek Rd and Caloutas Lane.
Bright area

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM CAIRN CURRAN 
  • MAJOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM LAANECOORIE RESERVOIR OVERNIGHT THURSDAY INTO FRIDAY 
  • MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LODDON WEIR AND APPIN SOUTH 
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in parts of the Loddon River, with renewed rises from overnight rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream through the catchment. Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall. 
  • Major flooding is occurring at Downstream Cairn Curran and expected at Downstream Laanecoorie Reservoir from overnight Thursday into Friday. Moderate flooding has is occurring along the Loddon River at Appin South. The Loddon River Downstream Loddon Weir is steady around the moderate flood level. 
  • In the 24 hours to 3:00 pm Thursday, rainfall totals of 40-65 mm have been observed across the Loddon River catchment. Further heavy rainfall is forecast for Thursday and into Friday.
Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie:
Major flooding is occurring along the Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie. The Loddon River Cairn Curran is currently at 3.58 metres and rising, with major flooding The Loddon River 
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 01:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Hughes Creek. 

MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING ALONG THE YEA RIVER, HUGHES CREEK AND SUNDAY CREEK.

Rapid and significant river level rises are occurring along the Goulburn River and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday. Major flooding is occurring along the Yea River, Hughes Creek and Sunday Creek, with river levels still rising. Major flooding is expected at Seymour imminently. Further rises are likely with forecast rainfall during Thursday.

Minor flooding is expected to extend downstream to Shepparton from Friday afternoon, with further rises to the moderate and major flood levels during Saturday. Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.

Additional widespread heavy rainfall is forecast for Thursday and into Friday and further river level rises are possible.

Hughes Creek:
Major flooding is occurring along the Hughes Creek at Tarcombe. Further rises are possible with forecast rainfall.

This Watch and Act message replaces the Watch & Act issued at 12.48pm on Thursday 13/10/2022 . 
People in low lying areas should move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Local roads and bridges may be affected by floodwater. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 10:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Fifteen Mile Creek
 at Great South.

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE OVERNIGHT THURSDAY AND MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT GRETA SOUTH 

Moderate flooding may occur along the Fifteen Mile Creek.
The Fifteen Mile Creek at Greta South is currently at 2.93 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 

The Fifteen Mile Creek at Greta South may reach the moderate flood level (4.20 m) overnight Thursday into Friday with forecast rainfall.

Rainfall will increase during Thursday and Friday as a cold front moves slowly eastwards. 

Minor flooding is occurring along the Fifteen Mile Creek and moderate flooding is possible from overnight Thursday. 

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Thursday, rainfall totals of 20-100 mm have been observed in the Ovens and King River catchments. Further rainfall totals of 50-120 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and into Friday.

A severe weather warning for heavy rainfall is current across the catchment

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.

At about the Moderate Flood Level (4.2m),
  • Along the Three Mile Creek, shallow flooding commences north of the Hume Freeway over low lying farmland, Gravel Pit Rd, and the South Wangaratta Industrial area including Tone Road near the GOTAFE paddocks and the CFA/SES Training Ground.
  • Around the One Mile Creek, Rattray Ave footbridge will be closed and low-level flooding is likely along roads and land in other areas including Swan and Bronmar Streets.
  • Above floor flooding is not expected at this level

A number of roads will be affected by flooding and may be closed including:
  • Snow Road, between the Hume Freeway and Laceby-Targoora Road
  • Greta Road near corner of Brian Higgins Drive impacting access to the airport from both north and south
  • Arundels Lane
  • Tone Road, at 3 Mile Creek
  • Clarkes Lane
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 04:30 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for Rochester. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

  • Floodwaters are rapidly rising. 
  • Major flooding is expected to impact Rochester on Friday from 10am, with the Campaspe River expected to peak on Friday afternoon.
  • The river is expected to rise to minor flood levels from 9pm Thursday.
  • The duration of the flood event is likely to be between seven and 10 days.
If you are located in Rochester, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • The relief centre that has been opened at at Echuca United Football Netball Club at 252 High Street Echuca. The facility may have capabilities for small domestic pets, preferably in cages.
  • Family or friends homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Rochester Hospital and Aged Care Facility will utilise the hospitals of Echuca, Shepparton, Bendigo and Castlemaine.
Northern Highway is most accessible route, but continue to check regular updates via the VicTraffic website.

When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
This warning is current to Thursday 7pm. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency.
  • For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Evacuation of homes is required.
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate is dangerous and may put your life at risk.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Local schools have been closed to until further notice pending floods to prevent people outside Rochester attending the community.
This flood may be similar to 2011, where 80 per cent of Rochester and its surrounding rural areas flooded. In this flood:
  • More than 250 properties had water above floor level with many people and properties isolated by floodwater.
  • Businesses in the town were impacted with most of the shops flooded.
  • Public areas near the Campaspe River were flooded and remained closed due to the risks of falling trees.
  • Many roads, community facilities and private properties were damaged.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 07:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge to Bandiana.
MODERATE FLOODING LIKELY AT BANDIANA OVERNIGHT THURSDAY INTO FRIDAY
 
MINOR FLOODING LIKELY AT MONGANS BRIDGE FROM THURSDAY EVENING AND KIEWA (MAIN STREAM) FROM FRIDAY MORNING 

  • River level rises are occurring in the Kiewa River in response to observed rainfall during the past 24 hours. 
  • Moderate flooding is likely to develop at Bandiana overnight Thursday into Friday. 
  • Minor flooding is likely to develop at Mongans Bridge from Thursday evening and Kiewa (Main Stream) from Friday morning. 
  • Further rises are likely with forecast rainfall. In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Thursday, widespread rainfall totals of 5-20 mm have been observed across the Kiewa River catchment. Further rainfall totals of 50-75 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday and Friday.

Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge:
River level rises are occurring along the Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge, and minor flooding is likely to develop from Thursday evening.

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 2.96 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. 

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is likely to reach the minor flood level (3.30 m) Friday morning.The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.95 metres and steady, with minor flooding.
 
Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge to Bandiana :
Moderate flooding is likely along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is likely to reach the moderate flood level (3.10 m) overnight Thursday into Friday.


Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home, and sheds may occur in some locations.
  • Flooding impacts in Mt Beauty / Tawonga result principally from the Kiewa River West Branch and breakout flows from Simmonds Creek which impact the area north of Simmonds Creek Road through to the Kiewa Valley Highway
  • Kiewa Valley Highway may be affected by floodwater., especially where local creeks may affect the road.
  • At Bandiana, the Murray Valley Highway at Bandiana is likely to flood,watch for likely road  closures.
  • In the Bandiana area near the river, you may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 09:00 pm or as the situation changes.

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Echuca. 
  • Coliban Water, following consultation with the Department of Health, advises that customers in Echuca should boil their drinking water until further notice.   
  • This advisory has been issued following excessive stormwater due to inclement weather entering one of our treated water storage tanks. 
  • This may compromise the safety of the drinking water. The tank has now been isolated.
  • Coliban Water will keep customers informed as the situation changes. 
If you are live or work within Echuca, you must boil tap water before drinking.
What you should do:

  • Coliban Water recommends customers should bring water to a rolling boil before being used by heating the water until a continuous and rapid stream of air bubbles is produced from the bottom of a pan or kettle. 
  • Kettles with automatic cut-off switches are suitable. Variable temperature kettles should be set to boil.     
  • After heating, water must be allowed to cool before using it, and be stored in a clean, closed container for later use. 
  • Care should be taken to avoid scalding injuries especially around children.       
Boiled water can be used for:  
  • Drinking  
  • Preparing beverages  
  • Washing and preparing food  
  • Preparing baby formula  
  • Brushing teeth  
  • Making ice.  
Unboiled water can be used for:
  • Washing your hands
  • Showering and bathing
  • Flushing toilets
  • Washing dishes (ensure dry before use)
  • Clothes and garden watering. 
Ensure water is not ingested whilst bathing.  

  • Consumption of unboiled water can cause gastro-like symptoms. If you experience any of these symptoms, please contact your GP and inform your GP of this advisory.  
  • Please share this advice with neighbours and friends in the affected area. 
  • Would owners of rented properties please ensure your tenants are aware of this advisory.
Impacts in your area:
  • If a water quality issue is detected, Coliban Water will work to address the issue and keep customers informed.
This message was issued by the Department of Health.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Lower Plenty (Main Road at Para Road)
properties.webBody:
This Flash Flood Watch and Act is being issued for Lower Plenty (Main Road at Para Road). 

  • Heavy rainfall is causing localised flash flooding. 
  • You can stay safe by avoiding flooded and low-lying areas. 
  • Floodwater can be very deep, rise quickly and move fast. 
  • Be aware that heavy rainfall may also increase the potential for landslides and debris across roads.
If you are located in Lower Plenty (Main Road at Para Road), you are in danger. You should immediately move indoors, away from floodwater. Do not enter floodwater.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are inside: 
  • Stay inside and be aware of rising floodwater. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

If you are outside: 
  • You should stay away from trees, drains, low lying areas, creeks, canals, culverts and floodwater. 
  • You should seek shelter indoors, away from floodwater. 

If you are driving: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Homes and buildings could be flooded. 
  • Power, water, sewerage and telephone services could be lost in the area. 
  • Roads or bridges could be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.   

The next update is expected by 13/10/2022 11:50 pm or as the situation changes.   

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility:

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.

MINOR FLOODING AT SHEPPARTON LIKELY FROM FRIDAY AFTERNOON.

Rapid and significant river level rises are occurring along the Goulburn River and its tributaries. Major flooding is occurring along the Yea River, Hughes Creek and Sunday Creek, with river levels still rising. Major flooding is expected at Seymour from Thursday evening. Further rises are expected with forecast rainfall during Thursday.

Minor flooding is expected to extend downstream to Shepparton from Friday afternoon, with further rises likely. Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated once upstream locations have peaked.

In the 24 hours to 11:00 am Thursday, widespread rainfall totals of 30-80 mm have been observed in the Goulburn River catchment. Further rainfall totals of 30-50 mm are forecast for the remainder of Thursday into Friday, with isolated higher totals possible.

Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton:

River level rises are likely along the Goulburn downstream of Shepparton from early next week.

The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 8.23 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain below the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Thursday and into Friday. River level rises are expected from early next week as upstream floodwaters arrive.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT COROWA, TORRUMBARRY AND STEVENS WEIR

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Kiewa River and the releases from Hume Dam, renewed minor flooding is possible at Albury from Friday.

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

Downstream along the Murray River, moderate flooding continues at Corowa and Torrumbarry. Major flooding is likely at Barham from Thursday afternoon. Floodwaters from the Murray River combined with floodwaters from the Edward River have caused minor flooding at Wakool Junction and may cause minor flooding at Boundary Bend from early next week. Minor flooding is possible at Wentworth around the end of October.

Along the Edward River, moderate flooding is occurring at Stevens Weir. Minor flooding continues at Deniliquin and Moulamein.

Further rainfall is forecast from the rest of Thursday into Friday which may cause renewed rises. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided as required.

Severe Weather Warning for heavy rainfall is current for Riverina Districts which covers Murray and Edward River catchments.

Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:

Moderate flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Corowa. Renewed minor flooding is possible at Albury. Minor flooding is possible at Yarrawonga.

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Kiewa River the Murray River at Albury may reach the minor flood level (4.30 m) Friday morning.

The Murray River at Corowa peaked around 6.21 metres on Sunday 09 September and is currently at 5.99 metres and falling slowly with moderate flooding. Subject to the inflows from the Kiewa River renewed river level rises are possible at Corowa. Predictions will be provided once the upstream peak levels are observed.

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Ovens River, the Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream may reach the minor flood level (6.40 m) during Monday.

Subject to tributary inflows the Murray River at Tocumwal may reach the minor flood level (6.40 m) over the weekend..
  • Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
  • Most of the flooding impacts are occurring on the NSW side of the Murray River
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria.  
  • For more information relevant to your area please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria  
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Parks, tracks and campgrounds maybe closed due to flooding
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Flash Flood Watch and Act is being issued for Beaufort. 

  • Heavy rainfall is causing localised flash flooding in Beaufort. 
  • You can stay safe by avoiding flooded and low-lying areas. 
  • Floodwater can be very deep, rise quickly and move fast. 
  • Be aware that heavy rainfall may also increase the potential for landslides and debris across roads.
If you are located in Beaufort, you are in danger. You should immediately move indoors, away from floodwater. Do not enter floodwater.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are inside: 
  • Stay inside and be aware of rising floodwater. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

If you are outside: 
  • You should stay away from trees, drains, low lying areas, creeks, canals, culverts and floodwater. 
  • You should seek shelter indoors, away from floodwater. 

If you are driving: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

You should stay informed by listening to local emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Many homes have become isolated by floodwater.
  • Flash flooding has impacted the Western Highway at Beaufort, King Street, Neil Street, Havelock Street, Willoby Street, High Street, Albert Street and Leichardt Street
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.   

The next update will be issued as the situation changes.   

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
The Bureau of Meteorology has issued a Severe Weather Warning for parts of Victoria. 

  • A deep low-pressure system south of the Great Australian Bight extends a strong cold front over western Victoria. The cold front is shifting slowly eastward over central parts of the state. This system is combing with a deep tropical air mass to cause widespread areas of heavy rainfall across central and northeastern parts of the state, as well as damaging to destructive wind gusts over elevated terrain.
  • HEAVY RAINFALL which may lead to FLASH FLOODING is forecast to continue.
  • The risk of heavy rainfall around Melbourne will be brief and most likely later this afternoon and evening.Rainfall rates are expected to ease from the west tonight, clearing during Friday morning.
  • Six-hourly rainfall totals between 30 to 50 mm are likely, with isolated heavier falls up to 65 mm. 24 hour rainfall totals are expected to reach 50 to 80 mm, with isolated totals up to 120mm over higher terrain.
  • Heavy rainfall increases the potential for landslides and debris across roads.
  • Northerly winds with DAMAGING WIND GUSTS with peak gusts of 90 to 100 km/h are likely over elevated terrain across central and eastern Victoria. Locally DESTRUCTIVE WIND GUSTS reaching up to 130 km/h are likely about exposed alpine peaks. Winds are expected to ease from the west later this evening, then clearing during Friday morning.
  • Flood Warnings and a Flood Watch are current for catchments across Victoria. See http://www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings  for more information.
  • Locations which may be affected include Bendigo, Shepparton, Seymour, Maryborough, Ballarat, Geelong, Melbourne,Wodonga and Wangaratta.
Do not attempt to drive through floodwaters - it could be the last decision you make.

Prepare to take shelter and be aware of potential hazards caused by the severe weather. Hazards include floodwater, debris, damaged building, trees down, fallen power lines.
What you should do: 

  • Park your car undercover and away from trees. 
  • Stay inside if conditions outside appear dangerous. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.   

If you are driving: 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
  • Be aware of road hazards such as mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • For road closure information, check the VicTraffic website, contact your local council or call VicRoads (13 11 70). 

Relief centres:
  • A relief centre has been activated in Creswick for people who are relocating from their homes. It is located at the Doug Lindsay Recreation Reserve.

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For severe weather related emergency assistance from the SES, phone 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
The potential impacts of severe weather in your area include: 
  • Building damage 
  • Fallen power lines 
  • Fallen trees and branches 
  • Flash flooding 
  • Landslides 
  • Overflowing drains and gutters 
  • Broken windows 
  • Damage to vehicles 
  • Flooding in properties and homes 
  • Dangerous road conditions
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.   

The next update is expected by 14/10/2022 12:10 am or as the situation changes.   

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicstorms) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
